            <h3 class="text-heading">NIGERIA UNION OF JOURNALISTS (NUJ) - THE JOURNEY SO FAR</h3>
            <p class="sample-text">
                Emergence of journalists’ agitation in Nigeria, which eventually led to the formation of a virile Union, Nigeria Union of Journalists (NUJ), is as old as the struggle for Independence itself. Most notable statesmen, who fought for self rule and extinct of Colonialism were Journalists/Politicians.
                These Nationalist members, like Herbert Macaulay, Dr Nnamdi Azikwe, Chief Obafemi Awolowo, Sir Ahmadu Bello, Sardauna of Sokoto, Chief Samuel Ladoke Akintola, Arnest Ikoli, to mention a few, were prolific writers and publishers of newspapers, pamphlets and magazines, instruments they judiciously used to attain self-rule.

            </p>

            <p class="sample-text">
                The Nigeria Youth Movement, the platform for nationali, trade unionism and professionalism led credence to vibrant media outbursts, especially print media, leading to emergence of powerful writers like <b>Alade Odunewu, Chief Bisi Onabanjo (Aye koto), Chief Lateef Jakande (John West), Abiodun Aloba, (Ebenezer Williams) Adamu Ciroma </b>, during and after Independence struggle. <br />
                For serious attacks on the government, example was the incarceration and jail terms by the likes of Professor Chike Obi who was jailed for sedition because of his writing “down with the enemies of the people”, as well as a prolific Editor of Ibadan based newspaper the Nigerian Tribune, Mr Ayo Ojewumi, (Pen Atalanta).
                It was not a surprise that these struggles and agitations, led to formal formation of Nigeria Union of Journalists NUJ, on March 15, 1955, though most of the pioneer fathers were, ironically, Government Information Officers.
                In its formation, more than 80 percent of members were in Lagos from Print, Radio and ministry of Information. The vibrancy of Ibadan based media like Nigerian Tribune, Western Nigeria Television (WNTV/WNBC) founded in 1959 and National Broadcasting Corporation NBC, later made the launching of Ibadan council of the NUJ possible, The Enugu/Eastern region closely followed with the efforts of Chief Hens, H. Offonry an executive member of NUJ. With the efforts of Correspondents, NUJ Kaduna was launched in 1958. Benin NUJ came on board in 1963 and by 1966, NUJ had 12 state councils.
            </p>

            <p class="sample-text">
                The need for Unionism emanated from claims of non-payment of salaries and poor conditions of service by many media owners, with claims that some of the journalists had little professional and academic laurels.
                Following the ideas by the more enlightened professionals, the heat for agitation for improved conditions of service from media owners was on high ebb.
                Mr Olu Oyesanya, an Information Officer in the department of Information, under colonial government, who had the opportunity to have travelled to United Kingdom, who in comparison with journalists welfare conditions over there, spearheaded the NUJ formation.
                At its second meeting in Lagos, NUJ constitution was ratified while the Unions executive was inaugurated in March 1955.
                They were:
