            <p class="sample-text">
                Nigeria Union of Journalists (NUJ), took off as a trade union organization, registered under the then Labour Cap 2000. The need for its restructuring was a debate, with Abiodun’s panel emphasizing for need for a trade Union experienced Secretary with industrial union background’, though this was critised by Sidi Sirajo-led group following opposition from the North. It was the November 1977 agreement between the North and Southern practitioners as well as a similar meeting in Benin, same year, that ratified the concept of Trade Unionism and professionalism for the NUJ, it also approved appointment of full time Secretary with industrial training.
                For long, NUJ suffered factional crisis which was a buildup of <b>Sidi Sirajo and Micheal Asaju’s leadership</b>. The Union eventually emerged with two presidents at Akure Congress in 1980, with <b>Alhaji Bola Adedoja</b> who was in firm control of the NUJ secretariat at Eric more in Lagos and Jola Ogunlusi, holding sway at the national secretariat.
            </p>

