                Ralp Igwa faction held its own election outside the convention hall in Akure.
                In 1984, the factions reunited under Alhaji Adedoja at a meeting in Minna, which was hosted by the then governor of Niger state, then Col. David Mark.
                In 1985, the NUJ constitution was amended and George Izobo defeated the incumbent, Alhaji Bola Adedoja at a keenly contested election.
                Since then, NUJ has been a united body, but is now more of a professional than a trade Union organisation. The check-off dues, its main source of sustenance has dwindled considerably.
            </p>

            <p class="sample-text">
                Oyo State Council of Nigeria Union of Journalists (NUJ), after its formation in the early 50 – 60s, experienced serious intimidation of its members, aftermath of the political instability in the Western region.
                The workers of the Tribune titles establishment by the first premier of the region, late Chief Obafemi Awolowo were always hunted by the security agents supportive of the National Democratic Party (NDP) of late Chief S.L. A Akintola. Its editor Mr Ayo Ojewumi was jailed while the Agbadagbudu Yemetu office of the newspapers was always raided. Nigeria Tribune and its vernacular sister Irohin Yoruba were usually published underground while buyers too could be arrested and prosecuted under the newspapers amended Act of 1964. To counter the Tribune excesses Akintola’s ruling party set up Morning Star and Imole Owuro, as opposition newspapers to Nigerian Tribune and Irohin Yoruba.
                The period later witnessed the birth of Daily Sketch; established by the regional government.
            </p>

            <p class="sample-text">
                Within this period, Journalists used to get together for social and labour activities along Eleyele recreation centre or Daily Times office, Oke Padre until the time that the military governor of Western state, then Col. Adeyinka Adebayo allocated a quarters of what is now known as NUJ Press centre, Simeon Adebo Avenue, Iyaganku Government Reservation Area, GRA Ibadan, the current seat of the Union in 1968s. <br />
                Notable among the vibrant NUJ practitioners who sought and got the allocation of the premises were <b>Chief Theophilous  Ola (Daily Times Bureau Chief), Hamed Alao (Daily Express) Remi Adebayo (Morning Post) Ajike Feyisayo, (Information) Alhaji Aliu who later rose to the post of Chief Information Officer, Dosu Ajayi Obe (Radio Nigeria) Lanre Yusuf (Daily Times) Adeola Basiru (Morning post) and Bisi Adebunmi (Daily Times)</b>.
                The pioneer officers were <b>Prince Isaac Adebayo Chairman and Mr Dosu Ajayi Obe Secretary 1968 – 1970, Alhaji Saka Fagbo, Chairman and Mr Peter Ajayi secretary 1971 – 1972, Joe Adentan, Chairman and Tola Adeniyi, secretary 1975 – 1976, Dotun Oloyede, Chairman and Eric Fawole, secretary <i>1976 – 77</i>, Lateef Abass Chairman and Biodun Famojuro, secretary 1977 – 1978, Bode Oyewole, chairman and Iyiola Lawal, secretary 1978 – 1980</b>.
                The NUJ, had a long drawn running battle in securing the premises from officers of the Ministry of Lands, Housing and Survey until during the regime of Sehinde Dagunduro (Chairman) and Bolaji Kareem (Secretary) 1987 – 1989 when late Governor Sasaenia Oresanya granted and signed the certificate of occupancy (C.O.).
            </p>

            <p class="smaple-text">
                The Oyo State Council of Nigeria Union of Journalists had experienced the good, the bad and the ugly moments from various governments. For the first time, the union under the leadership of Joe Abiola (Chairman) and Ranti Ajeleti 1983 – 1985 secured a Toyota bus from Governor Bola Ige’s administration and a Volkswagen Beetle car from Adegoke Motors. <br />
                The first expansion to the main building was the construction of Executive Council Chambers by Kemi Ogunyemi (Chairman) and Bolaji Kareem General Secretary. 1985 - 1987 as well as the tarring of the premises, by former Governor Adetunji Idowu Olurin, with the intervention of his Chief Press Secretary, Mr Lekan Alabi. Sehinde Dagunduro (Chairman)/Bolaji Kareem (secretary’s) executive ensured the introduction of Suya base, and current Administrative block through late Col, David Laoye’s Directorate of Employment.
            </p>

            <p class="smaple-text">
                <b>Dapo Aderogba (Chairman) and Lekan Awoyemi (secretary) </b> - led executive <i>1989 – 1991</i> created idea of a Guest House for members’ recreation.
                When a former secretary of the Union, <b>Alhaji Bolaji Kareem</b> became Commissioner for Works and Transport in Oyo State, he facilitated the building of the Hall, today named Dapo Aderogba Hall, following the request for such from the <b>Dapo Aderogba (Chairman) Lanre Ogundipe (secretary)</b> led executive 1992 – 1993.
                When Mr Lanre Ogundipe, succeeded late Aderogba as chairman in 1993 – 1995 he initiated the creation of Pen Group of Schools, (Primary/Secondary) to serve as model schools in the state. He later became a national president of the Union. Successive executives of Soladoye Adewole, Victor Oluwadamilare, Wale Ojo-Lanre relentlessly worked hard to build and sustain the schools which were almost crippled because of financial impediments, logistics and administration.
                These include building of more classrooms, resource centre and procuring of vehicles and free health facilities for the students, members and neighbours.
                Gbenga Opadotun’s administration also facilitated new vehicles apart from those secured by Wale Ojo-Lanre, for the Union, the Science Laboratory and Library, as well as another heath centre and New Guest House.
                Since the emergence of Comrade Adewumi Faniran led executive, 2016 to date union members had been reunited, NUJ premises had experienced facelifts, with improved condition of the schools the workers and welfare of the members. The executive has also embarked on updating registration of its members (old and new) enforcement of discipline as well as pursuit for befitting  good conditions of service and preparation for good insurance policy for its members.
